✅ What is catch‑all routing ([...slug].js) in Next.js?
Catch‑all routing in Next.js allows a single dynamic route file to handle multiple URL segments of varying depth.
It is useful when you don’t know in advance how many path segments a route will have.

🔹 Basic Idea
Using [...slug].js, you can match one or more URL segments with a single route.
pages/docs/[...slug].js
This file matches:
	• /docs/intro
	• /docs/getting-started
	• /docs/guides/setup
	• /docs/a/b/c
✅ One file → many URLs
✅ Dynamic depth supported

🔹 How the Route Parameter Works
For a URL like:
/docs/guides/setup
Inside [...slug].js:

import { useRouter } from 'next/router';
const router = useRouter();
console.log(router.query.slug);
Output:
["guides", "setup"]
📌 The parameter is always an array of path segments.

🔹 Typical Use Cases (Very Common in Interviews)
✅ Documentation websites
	• /docs/intro
	• /docs/api/auth
	• /docs/api/auth/login
✅ CMS‑driven pages
	• URLs defined by content editors
	• Flexible content hierarchies
✅ Knowledge bases / help centers

🔹 Catch‑All vs Dynamic Routes
Type	File	Matches
Dynamic route	[id].js	Exactly one segment
Catch‑all route	[...slug].js	One or more segments

🔹 Optional Catch‑All Routing ([[...slug]])

pages/docs/[[...slug]].js
``
Matches:
	• /docs
	• /docs/intro
	• /docs/a/b
📌 Difference:
	• [...slug] → requires at least one segment
	• [[...slug]] → segment is optional

🔹 With Data Fetching (Example)

export async function getStaticProps({ params }) {
  const { slug } = params; // array
  return { props: { slug } };
}
``
✅ Works with:
	• getStaticProps
	• getServerSideProps
	• ISR

🧠 Interview‑Ready 30‑Second Answer
	Catch‑all routing in Next.js uses [...slug].js to match routes with multiple URL segments.
	The matched segments are available as an array, making it ideal for documentation sites or CMS‑driven pages with dynamic URL structures.
	It allows flexible routing without defining routes for every possible path.

